                </a></li></ul></div><p><strong>Figure 4.  <span>Effect of a non-membrane permeable inhibitor of calmodulin on TRPV1-mediated Ca<sup>2+</sup>-transport.</span></strong></p><a id="article1.body1.sec2.fig4.caption1.p1" name="article1.body1.sec2.fig4.caption1.p1"></a><p>Camstatin, a recently identified, selective, 25-mer polypeptide blocker of calmodulin, was employed, which inhibited capsaicin-induced Ca<sup>2+</sup>-uptake with comparable activity (IC<sub>50</sub> = 20 ÂµM) determined previously to other, more conventional antagonists, of calmodulin in TRPV1-NIH3T3 cells. Results with camstatin suggests calmodulin-like structure at the extracellular domains of TRPV1. Experiments were repeated two additional times in triplicate with similar results.</p>
